      <h1 class='title'>PENSION LIBERATION: COURT'S POWER TO ORDER RESTITUTION</h1>
    </div>
    <div class='grand-committee-report-sitting' id='content'>
      
      <cite class='section'>HL Deb 08 July 2004 vol 663 cc185-6GC</cite>
      <a class='permalink column-permalink' id='column_185gc' title='Col. 185GC &mdash; HL Deb 08 July 2004 vol 663 c185GC' name='column_185gc' href='#column_185gc' rel='bookmark'>185GC</a>
      <p class='procedural'>
        <a class='permalink' href='#S5LV0663P0_20040708_GCR2_79' title='Link to this contribution' rel='bookmark'>&sect;</a>
        <ol>
        <li> This section applies where money has been liberated from a pension scheme.</li>
        <li> In this section "recoverable property" means (subject to subsection (3))&#x2014;</li>
        </ol>
      </p>
      
      <p class='procedural'>
        <a class='permalink' href='#S5LV0663P0_20040708_GCR2_80' title='Link to this contribution' rel='bookmark'>&sect;</a>
        <ol>
        <li> the money or any of it, or</li>
        <li> property (of any kind and wherever situated) that, directly or indirectly, represents any of the money.</li>
        <li> Where a person acquires the beneficial interest in recoverable property in good faith, for value and without notice that the property is, or (as the case may be) represents, money liberated from a pension scheme&#x2014;</li>
        </ol>
      </p>
      
      <p class='procedural'>
        <a class='permalink' href='#S5LV0663P0_20040708_GCR2_81' title='Link to this contribution' rel='bookmark'>&sect;</a>
        <ol>
        <li> the property ceases to be recoverable property, and</li>
        <li> no property that subsequently represents it is recoverable property.</li>
        <li> The court, on the application of the Regulator, may make such order as the court thinks just and convenient for the purpose of securing that recoverable property, or money representing its value or proceeds of its sale, is transferred&#x2014;</li>
        </ol>
      </p>
      
      <p class='procedural'>
        <a class='permalink' href='#S5LV0663P0_20040708_GCR2_82' title='Link to this contribution' rel='bookmark'>&sect;</a>
        <ol>
        <li> towards a pension scheme,</li>
        <li> towards an annuity or insurance policy, or</li>
        <li> to the liberated member.</li>
        <li> An order under subsection (4) may (in particular) direct a person who holds recoverable property, or has any degree of control over recoverable property, to take steps for the purpose mentioned in that subsection.</li>
        <li> Where the court makes an order under paragraph (a) of subsection (4), it may by order direct the trustees or managers of the scheme referred to in that paragraph&#x2014;</li>
        </ol>
      </p>
      
      <p class='procedural'>
        <a class='permalink' href='#S5LV0663P0_20040708_GCR2_83' title='Link to this contribution' rel='bookmark'>&sect;</a>
        <ol>
        <li> to take steps for the purpose mentioned in that subsection;</li>
        <li> to apply the property or money transferred, in such manner as the court may direct, for the purpose of providing benefits under that scheme to or in respect of the liberated member.</li>
        <col>GC 186</col>
        <li> Regulations may modify any of the provisions of the <a href="/acts/pension-schemes-act-1993">Pension Schemes Act 1993</a> (c. 48) as it applies in relation to cases where an order is made under subsection (6).</li>
        <li> The jurisdiction conferred by this section is exercisable by the High Court or the Court of Session.</li>
        <li> The generality of the jurisdiction conferred by section 17 is not to be taken to be prejudiced by this section.</li>
        <li> The generality of the jurisdiction conferred by this section is not to be taken to be prejudiced by section (<i>Pension liberation: repatriation orders</i>)."</li>
        </ol>
      </p>
      
      <q id='S5LV0663P0_20040708_GCR2_84'>
        After Clause 18, insert the following new clause&#x2014;
      </q>
      <ol class='xoxo'>
        
